in Analog Days, a book that explores the invention of the synthesizer and its impact on popular culture. The authors take us back to the heady days of the 1960s and early 1970s, when the technology was analog, the synthesizer was an experimental instrument, and synthesizer concerts could and did turn into happenings. Interviews with the pioneers who determined what the synthesizer would be and how it would be used--from inventors Robert Moog and Don Buchla to musicians like Brian Eno, Pete Townshend, and Keith Emerson--recapture their visions of the future of electronic music and a new world of sound. Tracing the development of the Moog synthesizer from its initial conception to its ascension to stardom in Switched-On Bach, from its contribution to the San Francisco psychedelic sound, to its wholesale adoption by the worlds of film and advertising, Analog Days conveys the excitement, uncertainties, and unexpected consequences of a new technology that would provide the soundtrack for a critical chapter of our cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMoog synthesizer. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Electronic.2bisacsh1 aMoog, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinch, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrocco, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674042162zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674042162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674042162/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK